   <text>
      <body>
         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Junction Hotel ¶ Drummond ¶ 1/4/84 ¶  ¶ I inclose an orchid for your confirmation Dear Baron I presume it is Pt. ¶  aphylla, but surely it is a misnomer for after the bloom is on some time a large ray...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">84.04.01</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From John McKibbin</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M49, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS annotation by M: 'Answ 24/4/84. FvM.' Letter not found.</p>
               </note>
               <note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Ms found with a specimen of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Pterostylis parviflora</seg> (MEL 1560857).</p>
               </note>Junction Hotel</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Drummond<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Vic.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">1/4/84</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I inclose an orchid for your confirmation Dear Baron I presume it is Pt.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Pterostylis</seg>.</p>
               </note> aphylla, but surely it is a misnomer for after the bloom is on some time a large ray of leaves spring from the thickened underground stem,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The inclosed and T. ixioedes<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Thelymitra%20ixioides">Thelymitra ixioides</name>
                     </seg>?</p>
               </note> are the only two kinds that I did not send to you obtainable in this district</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I hope soon to be able to send a few more perfect specimens of the Pt. you supposed to be Pt. Concinna when you will, I doubt not, see that it differs in many ways from that one — in fact it only agrees in having the double pointed labellum, with Pt. Concinna — It will be in bloom in a couple weeks or perhaps less when I shall send some specimens for your further examination</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Your obedient Servant</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>J. N. McKibbin</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Pterostylis%20aphylla">Pterostylis aphylla</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Pterostylis%20Concinna">Pterostylis Concinna</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Thelymitra%20ixioides">Thelymitra ixioides</name>
            </p>
         </div>
